<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-621-515  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 621 515.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 19 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Court grants Prime Computer stay of injunction. (United StatesCourt of Appeals, 6th Circuit, Massachusetts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Prime Computer Inc. (Cases)Virtual Maintenance Inc. (Cases).andO;Ticker:    PRM.andO;Topic:     Computer industryCourt CasesMaintenance ContractsAntitrust LawsLaw Suit.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COURT GRANTS PRIME COMPUTER STAY OF INJUNCTION 11/19/90 NATICK,MASSACHUSETTS, U.S.A., 1990 NOV 19 (NB) -- Prime Computer Inc. has announcedthat the United States Court of Appeals for the 6th Circuit has issued anemergency stay of an injunction ordered on November 15 by the United StatesDistrict Court in Detroit until the 6th Circuit can hold a hearing on Prime'sappeal of the injunction.andM;The injunction arose out of a lawsuit begun in 1989 by Virtual MaintenanceInc. against Prime, alleging that certain of Prime's maintenance policiesviolated federal antitrust laws.andP;  If reinstated, the injunction wouldprohibit Prime from using or enforcing contractual language in its softwareservice contracts with those customers who require the purchase of hardwaremaintenance.andM;Prime's announcement of the stay stated: &quot;Prime believes that the injunctionand the jury verdict in the case were wrong and Prime will file a motion inthe trial court to reverse the jury verdict in the case and will also appealthe verdict if the effort in the trial court is unsuccessful.andP;  In addition,Prime intends to ask the District Court to reverse the judge's treble-damageverdict in the amount of $25 million, and if the District Court denies thatrequest, Prime will appeal the verdict to the 6th Circuit Court.andP;  Primecontinues to believe that all of its policies and practices are legal and notin violation of antitrust laws, and will vigorously defend those policies.andO;They have served customers well and allow Prime to provide the highestquality of service.&quot;andM;Prime spokesperson Joe Gavaghan told Newsbytes that Prime's attorneys expectit to be a week to a week and a half before the appellate rules on theinjunction.&quot; Gavaghan also told Newsbytes that the petition to the DistrictCourt to overturn the jury verdict and reverse damages will proceed evenwhile the Court of Appeals considers the injunction.andP;  Gavaghan said: &quot;TheDistrict Judge has the power to overturn the verdict if he finds that it isnot supported by law and we are convinced that the jury finding was in sucherror.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19901119/Press Contact: Joe Gavaghan,Prime Computer Inc., 508-655-8000)</TEXT></DOC>